summary:
I reviewed the `test.sh` script, which attempts to verify the health check and an API call to `/api/data` through nginx. It expects the API endpoint to be working.

Then, I looked at `/etc/nginx/sites-available/default` and found that the reverse proxy was configured to direct requests to port `5001`.

```nginx
    # Reverse-proxy everything under /api/ to the Flask backend.
    location /api/ {
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5001;
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_connect_timeout 5s;
        proxy_read_timeout 30s;
    }
```

However, the Flask server was started on port `5000` (`curl -s http://127.0.0.1:5000/health` in `test.sh`).

I edited `/etc/nginx/sites-available/default` to point to port 5000 instead of 5001.

```nginx
<<<<
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5001;
====
        proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:5000;
>>>>
```

Then I ran `./test.sh` and it succeeded, passing all tests.
